posts.name: Benji Brunner
posts.cooked: Any possibility it’s a mechanical issue (e.g. too much friction in the elevator)? We had a similar issue, though we use a PID and have different rigging than a GrayT. Greasing all pulleys, axles, etc might help if you’re desperate

posts.name: Jeffrey Davis
posts.cooked:
These might seem like dumb questions but mignt help:

Are you holding in the A button during your test? The code you have cancels as soon as A is released so you have to keep holding it in.

Where did the P value come from? It seems very precise but if its not enough to move the elevator it might just be too low of a value ( or your other constants are too low)

Are there any other commands that could be running and cancelling this command? Something checking a sensor or a limit switch that is running any other command on the subsystem? (Remember a subsystem can only run one command at a time so any other commands will cancel this one).

Have your been able to move the elevator with simpler command? Set a voltage in the right direction and see if it moves? (Be ready on e stop for that one of course). Work your way up in steps like .1% power, 1% power, 5%, 10% and see if you start getting movement. By 50% you should definitely see something. No movement even with simple voltage means mechanical or wiring (or your going the wrong direction and should use negative voltages).
